BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cpKPbp09mJwFM0_fQ6ii6
SUMMARY:DUNE Mini-Comics Night
DTSTAMP:20260405T040301Z
DTSTART:20260428T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:DUNE* Mini-Comics Night is where folks are invited to create th
	e contents of a black and white\\\, 5.5” x 8.5” printed anthology within a
	 limited amount of time\\\, in one evening with no prompts or themes. Crea
	te whatever you want but it must be physical and finished by the end of th
	e night. \\nAn exclusive edition of the book will be published and distrib
	uted to only the contributors at the following DUNE meet-up. \\n \\nThis i
	s a night of communal productivity and creation with a deadline\\\, not ju
	st drinking and drawing. It is also meant to be a challenge to one’s abili
	ties to create a finished piece of self-satisfied work within the limitati
	ons. Bring the art supplies and paper that you are most comfortable workin
	g with and join dozens of illustrators and cartoonists on the 4th Tuesday 
	of each month from 5pm – 9pm. Space fills up quickly so be on time or you 
	may have to wait for space to create. \\n \\nAs always\\\, this is a commu
	nity funded project and we’ll ask for donations of $5 per submission for p
	rinting/publishing and renting the space at the historic Hugo House. Pleas
	e do our hosts a favor and order one drink minimum from the Book Bar. \\n 
	\\nAll are welcome! Don’t be a jerk! \\n \\n*There is no relation to DUNE 
	by Frank Herbert\\\, but you are welcome to submit DUNE inspired works. \\
	n \\n4th Tuesday of Each Month 5-9pm \\nHugo House \\n1634 11th Ave\\\, Se
	attle\\\, WA 98122 \\n \\nFree admission to this event is made possible wi
	th support from 4Culture.\n\nhttps://hugohouse.org/event/_2026-04-28/\n\nF
	rom Hugo House
URL:https://hugohouse.org/event/_2026-04-28/
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:hugo-house
CATEGORIES:Hugo House
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT4H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:0Tzgz2kZZKmX6JkP-e1cR
SUMMARY:Global Rhythms: Novalima
DTSTAMP:20260405T040301Z
DTSTART:20260428T193000Z
DESCRIPTION:Started by four friends from Lima with a shared passion for tra
	ditional Afro-Peruvian music and global DJ culture\\\, Novalima bridges pa
	st and future\\\, uniting tradition and innovation. \\nThe founders of Nov
	alima\\\, Ramon Perez-Prieto\\\, Grimaldo Del Solar\\\, Rafael Morales\\\,
	 and Carlos Li Carrillo\\\, became friends and started playing together in
	 Lima during high school\\\, playing a pivotal part in the 80s underground
	 hardcore punk and the 90s psychedelic/acid-rock scenes. Growing up\\\, Ra
	mon\\\, Grimaldo\\\, Rafael\\\, and Carlos listened to traditional Peruvia
	n folk music regularly in family gatherings and on the street\\\, while al
	so relentlessly explored new sounds in Rock\\\, Dub Reggae\\\, Latin and E
	lectronic Music\\\, which led to the delightful discovery of the fusion of
	 genres\\\, creating their unique sound. \\nAs they grew older\\\, distanc
	e drew them apart\\\, but the thrill of building new music brought them ba
	ck together. During their early experimentations blending Afro-Peruvian so
	unds with electronica\\\, the friends were scattered across the globe. Fro
	m their homes in London\\\, Barcelona\\\, Hong Kong \\\, and Lima they ema
	iled song ideas to each other. These long-distance recordings resulted in 
	their first album in 2002 album\\\, the self-titled Novalima. \\nKnown wor
	ldwide for breaking boundaries and uniting seemingly irreconcilable genres
	\\\, communities\\\, and generations\\\, Novalima has revolutionized the m
	usic scene in their native Peru by bridging a longstanding divide between 
	the mainstream and the minority Afro-Peruvian community\\\, who have strug
	gled against discrimination and cultural dissolution for generations. With
	 each album they seek new ways to connect the success and struggle of the 
	present to the unforgotten and sometimes painful history of the past. On o
	ne album\\\, they play with ancient sounds\\\, languages and instruments f
	rom the Andes and the Amazon. On another\\\, they highlight the new genera
	tion of artists around the world\\\, giving them an opportunity to reinter
	pret their African heritage. \\nNo matter the story they tell\\\, it’s har
	d to resist hip sway in the driving rhythms of their songs. \\nWatch: NOVA
	LIMA – La Danza (Official Video)\n\nhttps://townhallseattle.org/event/glob
	al-rhythms-novalima/\n\nFrom Town Hall Seattle
URL:https://townhallseattle.org/event/global-rhythms-novalima/
LOCATION:The Great Hall\\\, 1119 Eighth Avenue (enter on Eighth Avenue)\\\,
	 Seattle\\\, 98101\\\, United States
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:town-hall-seattle
CATEGORIES:Town Hall Seattle
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT
END:VEVENT
